 6.3\n|Jun low C = 9.3\n|Jul low C = 11.5\n|Aug low C = 11.4\n|Sep low C = 9.5\n|Oct low C = 6.6\n|Nov low C = 3.3\n|Dec low C = 1.9\n|year low C =\n|Jan precipitation mm = 53.97\n|Feb precipitation mm = 34.9\n|Mar precipitation mm = 42.29\n|Apr precipitation mm = 41.77\n|May precipitation mm = 45.38\n|Jun precipitation mm = 52.83\n|Jul precipitation mm = 39.38\n|Aug precipitation mm = 49.49\n|Sep precipitation mm = 51.71\n|Oct precipitation mm = 58.16\n|Nov precipitation mm = 54.14\n|Dec precipitation mm = 52.9\n|year precipitation mm =\n|source 1 = KNMI<ref name=\"Climate Normals 1971\u20132000\"/>\n|date=March 2011}}\n\n==Education==\n[[John Dee (mathematician)|John Dee]], noted Elizabethan philosopher, [[illusionist|magician]] and scientist and also responsible for the introduction to the first English translation of [[Euclid]], was educated at the [[King Edward VI Grammar School (Chelmsford)|Chantry School]] (later re-founded as the Grammar School) in the sixteenth century.\n\nChelmsford is also home to part of the [[Anglia Ruskin University]] (formerly called Anglia Polytechnic) and to the grammar schools of [[Chelmsford County High School]] and [[King Edward VI Grammar School (Chelmsford)|King Edward VI Grammar School]], founded in 1551 by charter of King Edward VI on the site of an earlier educational foundation (although evidence suggests it could have been around as early as 1292).\n\nA Catholic Secondary School in the area is [[St John Payne Catholic Comprehensive School]]. New Hall School, founded in 1642, is a private, Catholic boarding school which caters to pupils from the age of 3 right through to sixth form. The New Hall building, previously named [[Palace of Beaulieu]], has a great history including that of Henry VIII.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newhallschool.co.uk/ |title=Home |publisher=New Hall School |accessdate=30 August 2009}}</ref>\n\nChelmsford College is the main provider of further education in the city.  Established in the early 1960s, the college occupies three sites in the city.  The main site on Moulsham Street dates from the 1960s and the Princes Road site is a late 1980s building. There are around 2,200 full-time and 2,100 part-time students enrolled on a wide range of academic, vocational and occupational programmes. The College is rated as \"GOOD\" by OFSTED and holds the prestigious Investors in People (IiP) Champion status and is also an IiP Gold award holder.\n\nEducational establishments in Chelmsford include:\n\n*[[Anglia Ruskin University]]\n*[[King Edward VI Grammar School (Chelmsford)|King Edward VI Grammar School]]\n*[[St John Payne Catholic Comprehensive School]]\n*[[Writtle College]], an [[agricultural college]]\n*[[Great Baddow High School]]\n*[[Moulsham High School|Moulsham High School and humanities college]]\n*[[Hylands School|Hylands School Specialist Science and Sixth Form College]]\n*[[The Boswells School]]\n*[[Columbus School and College]]  \n*[[Chelmer Valley High School]]\n*[[New Hall School]]\n*[[Chelmsford County High School for Girls]]\n*[[Thriftwood School and College]]\n*[[St Peter's College, Chelmsford|St Peter's College]], the former Rainsford High School, which closed in August 2011.<ref>{{cite web |author=pdent-jones |url=http://www.thisistotalessex.co.uk/chelmsford/EXCLUSIVE-St-Peter-s-School-Chelmsford-shut/article-730133-detail/article.html |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120917130034/http://www.thisistotalessex.co.uk/chelmsford/EXCLUSIVE-St-Peter-s-School-Chelmsford-shut/article-730133-detail/article.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=17 September 2012 |title=EXCLUSIVE: St Peter's College in Chelmsford to shut |publisher=Thisistotalessex.co.uk |accessdate=17 September 2010 }}</ref>\n*[[The Sandon School]]\n*[[Chelmsford College]], a college of [[further education]]\n*[[The Bishop's C of E & R C Primary School]], which has the distinction of being one of the few joint Anglican and Roman Catholic primary schools in the country<ref>{{cite web|title=About us|url=http://www.bishops.essex.sch.uk/About%20Us.htm|publisher=The Bishops' C of E & R C Primary School|accessdate=31 July 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150703171220/http://www.bishops.essex.sch.uk/About%20Us.htm|archivedate=3 July 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref><!-- Not notable enough for an article but seems worth a mention here; redirecting stub article to this article. -->\n\n==Society and culture==\n\n===Media===\nChelmsford is home to local radio station [[Chelmsford Radio]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chelmsfordradio.co.uk |title=Chelmsford Radio |publisher=Chelmsford Radio |accessdate=17 September 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100821121731/http://www.chelmsfordradio.co.uk/ |archive-date=21 August 2010 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> but it does not broadcast from the city. The station recently moved to studios in [[Southend]] having vacated its [[Heybridge, Maldon|Heybridge]] premises on 12 January 2009. The station was originally situated in Chelmsford city centre in Cater House until November 2006. This station was previously known as Dream 107.7 until February, and before that, 107.7 Chelmer FM up to 2002. The station began broadcasting on 18 October 1998. It is the local station for mid-[[Essex]]. [[Adventure Radio]] have owned this station since 2008, where it was purchased from Tindle Radio Ltd. As of 19 February 2015, Chelmsford and Southend Radio re-branded and merged to form [[Radio Essex]],<ref>[[Southend Radio]]</ref>\n\nChelmsford also has a local opt-out of [[The Heart Network|Heart FM]]. [[Heart Essex (regional)|Heart Essex]] (previously Essex FM up to June 2009) has been on air since 12 September 1981 and has been owned by [[Global Radio]] since 2007. It moved to studios in Glebe Road in late 2004, having previously been based in [[Southend-on-Sea]]. In May 2009, the station was rebranded to The Heart of Essex, Essex FM. In June 2009, the popular Essex FM n\u00e9e Essex Radio name brand was dropped after 28 years. On 3 June 2019 Heart Essex was closed as part of wider changes to the Heart network. It was replaced by [[Heart East]] with programs coming from studios in London and Milton Keynes. The Chelmsford studio was closed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.essexlive.news/news/essex-news/listeners-boycott-heart-essex-after-2946391|title=Listeners boycott Heart Essex after presenters Martin and Su leave|last=Finnegan|first=Sophie|date=2019-06-06|website=essexlive|access-date=2019-06-07}}</ref>\n\n[[BBC Essex]] has been on air since 5 November 1986 and its studios are based in New London Road.\n\nThere is a local  Award-winning, Hospital Radio Station based out of Broomfield Hospital, known as Hospital Radio Chelmsford, the station has been running since 1964 and is supported by volunteers. The station broadcasts 24 hours for patients at the hospital but can also be listened to online and via the app.\n\nSince 2014, local community station CCR (Chelmsford Community Radio) has broadcast to the city via the internet. In 2015 the station won an FM community licence and launched in early 2017 on 104.4FM.\n\nUntil their closure in the mid-2000s [[Anglia Television]]/ITV Anglia had offices located in Chelmsford city centre. Chelmsford is served by London and East Anglia regional variations of the BBC and ITV1.\n\nPublications based in Chelmsford include the ''[[Essex Chronicle]]'', which was founded as the ''Chelmsford Chronicle'' in 1764. The weekly ''Essex Chronicle'' newspaper is the longest in continuous publication in the country.{{Citation needed|date=December 2007}} Until the closure of the printing plant in 2002, the paper was also printed in the town. It is now printed on presses by the [[Reach Plc]] Group which now owns the paper. ''[[Chelmsford Weekly News]]'' is a free local paper which ceased production in June 2017. Another popular publication is the free \"Edge\" magazine, a primarily volunteer effort aimed at older Chelmsfordians. ''The Face of Chelmsford'' is a monthly magazine delivered to 12,500 homes in Chelmsford that has now become a digital publication updated daily. ''City Life'' is a newspaper produced by Chelmsford City Council that is distributed throughout the area.\n\n===Religion===\n[[Chelmsford Cathedral]] is the second smallest cathedral in England after [[Derby Cathedral]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Cathedrals in the East of England: Chelmsford Cathedral|url=http://www.easterncathedrals.org.uk/chelmsford.html|accessdate=8 August 2012}}</ref>  It was built in the 15th and early 16th centuries, when it was the parish church of the prosperous medieval town. The [[Diocese of Chelmsford]] was established in 1914 from part of the [[Diocese of St Albans]]. It covers all of Essex and much of East London.\n\nChelmsford is also situated in the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Brentwood]] and the two dioceses are now uniquely (at least within England) conterminous. With the coming of the [[Protestant Reformation|Reformation]] the Catholic community of Chelmsford was subjected to the anti-Catholic laws and Chelmsford was the site of the death of a Catholic martyr, Saint [[John Payne (martyr)|John Payne]]. In the 19th century, native Catholics resurfaced and immigrants helped to build up the Catholic community. There are now three Catholic churches within Chelmsford along with a [[Norbertine]] [[canonry]] situated on New London Road; [[St. Philip's Priory]] and one of the largest Catholic private boarding schools in the country, [[New Hall School]].\n\nOther denominations are also represented, the [[Baptists]], [[Jehovah's Witnesses]], [[Seventh-day Adventist Church]], [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] and the [[United Reformed Church]] all have places of worship within the city. For the local Muslim community, the majority of which are Bengali and Pakistani, the Main Jamia Masjid mosque is located on Moulsham Street at the junction with Parkway.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chelmsfordmosque.co.uk/ContactUs.php |accessdate=10 November 2010 }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chelmsfordmosque.co.uk/index.php/news/115-vacancy-for-imam-at-chelmsford-masjid|title=Vacancy For Imam at Chelmsford Masjid|author=Chelmsfod Mosque|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Sport===\n[[Essex County Cricket Club]] is one of the 18 [[first-class cricket|first-class]] county clubs that make up the [[County cricket|English domestic cricket structure]], representing the county of Essex. The club is based at the [[County Cricket Ground, Chelmsford|County Ground]] in New Writtle Street close to the city centre.\n\n[[Chelmsford City F.C.|Chelmsford City Football Club]] plays in the [[National League South]]. The club's home ground is at the Chelmsford Sport and Athletics Centre, Melbourne Park, which it shares with Chelmsford Athletic Club. Chelmsford is one of the largest settlements in England without a [[Football League]] team. The city is also home to the Chelmsford Sunday League, of which there are five divisions consisting of teams from around the area. The former ground of the club{{which|date=December 2019}} the [[New Writtle Street Stadium]] also hosted [[Greyhound racing in the United Kingdom|greyhound racing]] which was one of two venues to do so. The other was at Springfield on local farmland on Pump Lane corner which took place during April 1949.{{clarify|date=December 2019}} The racing at both was independent (not affiliated to the sports governing body the [[National Greyhound Racing Club]]) and they were known as flapping tracks, which was the nickname given to independent tracks.<ref>{{cite book|last=Barnes|first=Julia|title=Daily Mirror Greyhound Fact File, page 413|year=1988|publisher=Ringpress Books|isbn=0-948955-15-5}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://greyhoundracingtimes.co.uk/?s=chelmsford|title=Chelmsford|publisher=Greyhound Racing Times}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Chelmsford R.F.C.|Chelmsford Rugby Football Club]] was established in 1920 and for the last 40 years has been playing rugby at Coronation Park in Timpsons Lane.  As of 2016 the club has over 300 members and fields up to five senior teams each week. The club as of 2016 plays in the [[London 1 North]] league, the sixth tier of English rugby. In addition to the senior teams, there are 150 youth members providing teams from under 6's to under 17's. [[Chelmsford Hockey Club]] is a men's and ladies' field hockey club based in the city. It fields eight men's teams and five ladies' teams every weekend.{{citation needed|date=July 2016}} The Ladies' 1st XI compete in the [[Women's England Hockey League|English Hockey League]] Conference East as of July 2016.\n\n[[Chelmsford Swimming Club]] has been running for over 100 years and is located in the [[Riverside Ice and Leisure]] building in Chelmsford.<ref>{{cite news|title=Metropolitan Districts|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article19496904|accessdate=16 May 2015|publisher=The Brisbane Courier|date=13 November 1906|quote=The Chelmsford Swimming Club held a carnival in the Manly Baths.}}</ref> Also based in the same building are the [[Chelmsford Chieftains]], an ice hockey team that plays in the [[English National Ice Hockey League]].  The club promotes the use of junior players and local players from the Chelmsford and Essex area.\n\n[[Team Essex Volleyball Club]] is Chelmsford's national league volleyball club. It has four teams, which play in [[Volleyball England]]'s national volleyball league. Its men's 1st team currently competes in the top division in the country, the Super 8s, while the women's 1st team competes one tier below the men. The club has a strong junior program and trains in [[The Boswells School]] in Chelmsford.\n\n[[Horse racing]] has been run at two separate venues using the name Chelmsford, neither actually in the city centre itself. The sport originally took place at [[Chelmsford Racecourse]], at [[Galleywood]], from the 18th century until its closure in 1935.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hawkins|first1=Ted|title=Galloping Galleywood|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/essex/content/articles/2008/04/24/galleywood_race_course_feature.shtml|website=bbc.co.uk|accessdate=2 March 2015}}</ref> A new racecourse was established at [[Great Leighs]] in 2008 and subsequently changed its name to [[Chelmsford City Racecourse]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Racing back at 'Great Leighs'|url=http://www.racehorseowners.net/en/news/index.cfm/2015fixtures|website=racehorseowners.net|accessdate=2 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402090342/http://www.racehorseowners.net/en/news/index.cfm/2015fixtures|archive-date=2 April 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nSince 2014 the city has held a marathon. Starting and ending in the city centre, the marathon takes in the city itself and the surrounding environs. The 2014 edition had over 1000 participants.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.essexchronicle.co.uk/Chelmsford-marathon-2015-start-Shire-Hall/story-26236352-detail/story.html|title=Chelmsford marathon 2015 will start from Shire Hall|accessdate=21 February 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150730170612/http://www.essexchronicle.co.uk/Chelmsford-marathon-2015-start-Shire-Hall/story-26236352-detail/story.html|archive-date=30 July 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The Chelmsford campus of [[Anglia Ruskin University]] also has many sports teams and facilities.\n\n==Notable people born in Chelmsford==\n[[File:tindal.jpg|thumb|Statue of Sir [[Nicholas Conyngham Tindal]], Tindal Square Chelmsford.]]\n* [[Najma Akhtar]] (born 1962), jazz singer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.enotes.com/contemporary-musicians/najma-biography |title=Najma Biography: Contemporary Musicians |publisher=Enotes.com |accessdate=30 August 2009}}</ref>\n* [[Tom Bury]] (born 1958), first-class cricketer\n* [[Liam Chilvers]] (born 1981), professional footballer.<ref>{{cite web|last=Dewhurst |first=Tony |url=http://www.lep.co.uk/pnenews/Big-Interview-Liam-Chilvers.4303951.jp |title=Big Interview: Liam Chilvers \u2013 Lancashire Evening Post |publisher=Lep.co.uk |accessdate=30 August 2009}}</ref>\n*[[Noah Chilvers]] (born 2001), professional footballer.\n* [[Sarah Cracknell]] (born 1967), singer, [[Saint Etienne (band)|Saint Etienne]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/artists/saint-etienne |title=Saint Etienne \u2013 news, pictures, reviews, biography, videos, best songs, discography, books, DVDs, concerts, gossip, pictures and tour dates |work=NME  |location=UK  |date=17 July 2009 |accessdate=30 August 2009}}</ref>\n* [[Hazell Dean]] (born 1952), singer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1938453/|title=Hazell Dean|work=IMDb}}</ref>\n* [[James Gibson (swimmer)|James Gibson]] (born 1980), swimmer.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sportcentric.com/vsite/vcontent/page/custom/0,8510,5157-182674-199892-43108-270651-custom-item,00.html |title=British Swimming & The ASA : James Gibson MBE |publisher=Sportcentric.com |date=6 February 1980 |accessdate=30 August 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080908052930/http://www.sportcentric.com/vsite/vcontent/page/custom/0,8510,5157-182674-199892-43108-270651-custom-item,00.html |archive-date=8 September 2008 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* [[Greg Halford]] (born 1984), professional footballer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.expressandstar.com/2009/07/15/halford-happy-to-be-mr-versatile/ |title=Halford happy to be Mr Versatile : Express & Star |publisher=Expressandstar.com |date=15 July 2009 |accessdate=30 August 2009}}</ref>\n* [[Philemon Holland]] (born 1552), translator.<ref>{{Cite ODNB |url=https://www.oxforddnb.com/view/10.1093/ref:odnb/9780198614128.001.0001/odnb-9780198614128-e-13535 |title=Holland, Philemon (1552\u20131637) |last=Considine |first=John |date=23 September 2004 |doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/13535|access-date=6 February 2019}}</ref> \n*[[Cameron James]] (born 1998), professional footballer.\n* [[Harry Judd]] (born 1985), drummer, [[McFly]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.echo-news.co.uk/news/1790431.girls_line_up_to_meet_mcfly_in_leigh/ |title=Girls line up to meet McFly in Leigh (From Echo) |publisher=Echo-news.co.uk |date=27 October 2007 |accessdate=30 August 2009}}</ref>\n* [[George Clift King]] (born 1848), former Mayor of [[Calgary, Alberta|Calgary]], Alberta, Canada.<ref>{{cite web|title=City of Calgary Archives|url=http://www.calgary.ca/DocGallery/BU/cityclerks/k.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110610225228/http://www.calgary.ca/DocGallery/BU/cityclerks/k.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-date=10 June 2011|publisher=City of Calgary|accessdate=6 October 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* [[Anne Knight]] (born 1786), anti-slavery campaigner and pioneer of feminism.<ref>{{cite web|title=Key historical individuals|url=http://www.understandingslavery.com/teachingslavetrade/introduction/keyhistorical/?page=4|publisher=Understanding Slavery|accessdate=6 October 2009 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080701125330/http://www.understandingslavery.com/teachingslavetrade/introduction/keyhistorical/?page=4 |archivedate = 1 July 2008}}</ref>\n* [[Malcolm O'Kelly]] (born 1974) [[Ireland national rugby union team|Irish international]] [[rugby union]] player.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/sport/walking-tall-after-so-many-highs-1.664017|title=Walking tall after so many highs|last=Thornley|first=Gerry|date=12 May 2010|website=The Irish Times|language=en|access-date=6 February 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Tom Payne (actor)|Tom Payne]] (born 1982), ''[[Waterloo Road (TV series)|Waterloo Road]]'' actor.<ref>{{cite news|last=Rampton |first=James |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/5187959/On-set---Best-His-Mothers-Son.html |title=On set \u2013 Best: His Mother's Son |newspaper=Telegraph |date=25 April 2009 |accessdate=30 August 2009 | location=London}}</ref>\n* [[Grayson Perry]] (born 1960) [[Turner prize]]-winning artist.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/3299335.stm |title=Entertainment &#124; Profile: Turner winner Grayson Perry |work=BBC News |date=8 December 2003 |accessdate=30 August 2009}}</ref>\n* [[Sarah Perry]] (born 1979) Writer.<ref>sarahperry.moonfruit.com</ref>\n* [[Richard Spare]] (born 1951) Artist.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.art-press.co.uk/collections/richard-spare|title=Richard Spare - ArtPress Publishing|website=www.art-press.co.uk}}</ref>\n* [[Nigel Spink]] (born 1958), professional footballer and European Cup winner as well as junior goalkeeper at Writtle Minors football club.<ref>{{cite web|last=Swindells |first=Matt |url=http://www.wigantoday.net/latics/Spink39s-been-there-done-that.3780094.jp |title=Spink's been there, done that |publisher=Wigan Today |accessdate=30 August 2009}}</ref>\n* [[Joseph Strutt (engraver and antiquary)|Joseph Strutt]] (born 1742), engraver and antiquary.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chestofbooks.com/reference/American-Cyclopaedia-6/Joseph-Strutt.html |title=Joseph Strutt |publisher=Chestofbooks.com |accessdate=17 September 2010}}</ref>\n* Sir [[Nicholas Conyngham Tindal]] (born 1776), lawyer, judge and [[Lord Chief Justice of the Common Pleas]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000225/18460710/013/0002|title=Death of Lord Chief Justice Tindal|last=|first=|date=10 July 1846|work=The Chelmsford Chronicle|access-date=16 February 2019|issue=3942|page=2|via=[[British Newspaper Archive]]}}</ref>\n* [[James Harper (footballer)|James Harper]] (born 1980), professional footballer.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-15051750_ITM |title=Article: Harper snubs Ghana. &#124; AccessMyLibrary \u2013 Promoting library advocacy |publisher=AccessMyLibrary |date=27 April 2006 |accessdate=30 August 2009}}</ref>\n* [[Peter Collins (footballer)|Peter Collins]] (born 1948), professional footballer, Chelmsford City and Tottenham Hotspur.<ref>{{cite web|last=Swindells |first=Matt |url=http://www.justcatnaps.com/collection/GoodisonTottenhamParade |title=tottenham 1971 |publisher=spurs history |accessdate=30 August 2009 }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n* [[Guthrie Govan]] (born 1971), professional jazz/rock/fusion guitar player.\n* [[Jon Morter]] (born 1974), Campaigner, best known for UK Christmas No.1 chart campaigns with [[Rage Against the Machine]] and [[The Justice Collective]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm3937572/|title=Jon Morter|work=IMDb}}</ref>\n* [[Mike Edmonds]]  (born 1944), notable [[dwarfism|dwarf]] actor.\n* [[Alex Dowsett]]  (born 1988), professional cyclist.\n* [[Ronald Skirth]] (born 1897), World War I veteran who became a pacifist during the war and purposely miscalculated British guns.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=YhhgGrK2Ik3HevTTQZSkzQ&scan=1|title=Index entry\u2014Births March 1898\u2014Skirth John Ronald, Chelmsford 4a 571|accessdate=22 September 2010|work=FreeBMD|publisher=[[Office for National Statistics]]}}</ref>\n* [[Joe Thomas (actor)|Joe Thomas]] (born 1983), actor.\n* [[Squarepusher|Tom Jenkinson]] (born 1975), a.k.a. Squarepusher, English [[electronic music]] artist.\n* [[Ceephax Acid Crew|Andrew Jenkinson]] (born 1975), a.k.a. Ceephax Acid Crew, English [[electronic music]] artist.\n* Sir [[Walter Mildmay]] (born 1525), [[Chancellor of the Exchequer of England]] under [[Elizabeth I of England|Queen Elizabeth I]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.geni.com/people/Sir-Walter-Mildmay/6000000007606840010|title=Walter Mildmay, MP (c.1521 - 1589) - Genealogy|work=geni_family_tree}}</ref>\n* [[Tom McRae]] (born 1969), English [[singer-songwriter]].\n* [[J. A. Baker|John Alec Baker]] (born 1926), Writer and naturalist, best known for The Peregrine and the Hill of Summer.\n* [[Penny Lancaster]] (born 1971), [[Model (person)|model]] and [[photographer]]. Married to rock singer [[Rod Stewart]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1519592/bio?ref_=nm_ov_bio_sm|title= Penny Lancaster: Biography|accessdate=21 February 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Steve Blame]] (born 1959), Video Jockey on [[MTV]] \n* [[Carole Lesley]] (born 1935), \"Blonde bombshell\" actress of the late 1950s and early 1960s.\n* [[Gus Kenworthy]] (born 1991), freestyle skier.\n* [[Reg Webb]] (born 1947), Musician.\n*[[Ed Woodward]] (born 1971), CEO of [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United.]] \n* [[Nathan French]] (born 1990), Olympic volleyball player.\n* [[Felix (musician)]] (born Francis Wright), a British producer and DJ known for his hit 1992 track \"Don't you want me\" and his underground house project \"the Party Crashers\".\n* [[Richard Dannatt|The Lord Dannatt]] (born 1950), British Army officer, member of the House of Lords and [[Chief of the General Staff]] (head of the Army) from 2006 to 2009.\n* [[Sam Cook]] (born 1997), cricketer for Essex County Cricket Club.\n\n==Nearest places==\n{{Geographic location\n|title     = '''Destinations from Chelmsford'''\n|Northwest = [[Stansted Airport]], [[Bishops Stortford]], [[Great Dunmow]]\n|North     = [[Braintree, Essex|Braintree]]\n|Northeast = [[Witham]], [[Colchester]]\n|West      = [[Harlow]], [[Hertford]]\n|Centre    = Chelmsford\n|East      = [[Maldon, Essex|Maldon]], [[Heybridge, Maldon|Heybridge]], [[Danbury, Essex|Danbury]]\n|Southwest = London, [[Brentwood, Essex|Brentwood]], [[Ingatestone]]\n|South     = [[Basildon]], [[Billericay]], [[Tilbury]], [[Grays]]\n|Southeast = [[Southend on Sea]], [[Rochford]], [[Rayleigh, Essex|Rayleigh]], [[South Woodham Ferrers]]\n}}\n\n==Twin towns==\nChelmsford's official [[Town twinning|twin towns]] are:<ref name=\"Chelmsford twinnings\">{{cite web|url=http://www.chelmsfordtowntwinning.org.uk/ChelmsfordTownTwinningAssociationHome.aspx|title=Chelmsford Town Twinning Association|accessdate=14 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130517111507/http://chelmsfordtowntwinning.org.uk/ChelmsfordTownTwinningAssociationHome.aspx|archive-date=17 May 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chelmsford.gov.uk/index.cfm?articleid=8406 |title=Chelmsford Borough Council \u2013 Twin Towns |publisher=Chelmsford.gov.uk |accessdate=17 September 2010}}</ref>\n\n*{{flagicon|FRA}} [[Annonay]], [[Ard\u00e8che]], [[Auvergne-Rh\u00f4ne-Alpes]], France<ref name=\"Chelmsford twinnings\"/>\n*{{flagicon|GER}} [[Backnang]], [[Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg]], Germany<ref name=\"Chelmsford twinnings\"/>\n\nThe city also has a sister city:\n\n*{{flagicon|CHN}} [[Wuxi]], China<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/m/jiangsu/wuxi/2015-01/19/content_19346945.htm |title=Chelmsford - China Daily|newspaper=China Daily |accessdate=9 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Further reading==\n* Foreman, Stephen: ''Hylands \u2013 the story of an Essex country house and its owners'' (Ian Henry Publications, 1999)\n* Lee, Janet Olivia: ''Chelmsford \u2013 Birthplace of Radio'' (Chelmsford Borough Council, 2001)\n* Lowen, Ceri: ''Hylands House \u2013 a brief history and guide'' (Chelmsford Borough Council, 2005)\n* Wander, Tim: ''2MT Writtle \u2013 The birth of British Broadcasting'' (Capella Publications, 1988)\n* Weller-Lewis, Hugh: ''Chelmsford Borough Guide'' (Macmillan, 1995)\n* Wickenden, Nick: ''A Celebration of Chelmsford'' (Chelmsford Borough Council, 1999)\n* ''A town, its people and its past'' (Chelmsford Record Office, 1988)\n* Grieve, Hilda: ''The Sleepers and the Shadows Volume 2 Chelmsford: a town, its people and its past'' (Chelmsford Record Office, 1994)\n* Begent, Andrew: ''Chelmsford At War'' (Ian Henry Publications Ltd, 1999)\n* Torry, Gilbert: ''Chelmsford through the ages'' (East Anglian Magazine Ltd, 1977)\n* John Alec Baker:'' The Peregrine'','' The Hill of Summer'' and ''Diaries'' (Collins, 2011)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n{{wikivoyage|Chelmsford (England)}}\n* [http://www.chelmsford.gov.uk/ Chelmsford City Council]\n\n{{Essex}}\n{{London commuter belt}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2017}}{{Use British English|date=April 2012}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Chelmsford| ]]\n[[Category:County towns in England]]\n[[Category:Market towns in Essex]]\n[[Category:Archaeological sites in Essex]]\n[[Category:City of Chelmsford]]\n[[Category:Towns in Essex]]\n[[Category:Former national capitals]]\n", "name_user": "Cnwilliams", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:Sam Cook\u2192Sam Cook (Essex cricketer)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chelmsford"}
{"title_page": "Deng (surname)", "text_new": "{{distinguish|text=the surnames [[Teng (surname)|Teng]] ''(\u6ed5)'' or [[T\u00e1ng (surname)|T\u00e1ng]] ''(\u5510)''}}\n{{Infobox surname\n| name            = \u9127/\u9093\n| image           = \n| image_size      = \n| caption         = \n| romanization    = Teng ( [[Wade-Giles]] <br> [[Cantonese]]: Dahng ([[Yale romanization of Cantonese|Yale]]), Dang6 ([[Jyutping]]) <br>[[Southern Min|Minnan]]/[[Taiwanese Minnan|Taiwanese]]: T\u0113ng'' ( [[Pe\u030dh-\u014de-j\u012b]]) <br> [[Vietnamese language|Vietnamese]]: \u0110\u1eb7ng  <br>  [[Korean language|Korean]]: Deung )\n| pronunciation   = D\u00e8ng\n| gender          = \n| feminine        = \n| masculine       = \n| language        = \n| languageorigin  = \n| origin          = [[Nanyang, Henan|Nanyang]], Henan [[Chinese clan#Tang hao|ancestral hall]] ({{lang|zh|\u5357\u967d\u5802}})\n| derivation      = \n| meaning         = \n| variant         = \n| cognate         = \n| anglicisation   = \n| derivative      = \n| seealso         = \n| family          = \n}}\n'''Deng''' is an [[East Asia]]n [[surname]] of Chinese origin. It is a transcription of [[wikt:\u9093|\u9093]] ([[simplified Chinese character]]) or [[wikt:\u9127|\u9127]] ([[Traditional Chinese character|traditional]]). It is transliterated as ''D\u00e8ng'' in [[pinyin]] and Teng, or Then, in [[Wade-Giles]]. In [[Cantonese]], it is ''Dahng'' in [[Yale romanization of Cantonese|Yale]] and ''Dang6'' in [[Jyutping]].  In [[Southern Min|Minnan]] or [[Taiwanese Minnan|Taiwanese]], it is ''T\u0113ng'' in [[Pe\u030dh-\u014de-j\u012b]]. The surname originating from the same Chinese character in [[Vietnamese language|Vietnamese]] is ''\u0110\u1eb7ng'' and it is one of the top ten surnames in [[Vietnam]]. The name is transliterated as ''Deung'' in [[Korean language|Korean]] but is very rare in [[Korea]]. Deng is one of the surnames of the [[Nanyang, Henan|Nanyang]], Henan [[Chinese clan#Tang hao|ancestral hall]] ({{lang|zh|\u5357\u967d\u5802}}).\n\nIn 2019 Deng was 21st most common surname in Mainland China.<ref>http://www.bjnews.com.cn/news/2020/01/20/676822.html</ref>\n\nIn addition to spelling \"Deng\" used in [[mainland China]], other common Chinese spelling variations include:\n* '''Tang''' - Romanization based on Cantonese spelling common in [[Hong Kong]] and [[Macao]]\n* '''Teng''' - Romanization based on Wade-Giles transliteration of [[Standard Mandarin|Mandarin Chinese]] common spelling in [[Taiwan]]\n\n==Notable persons with the surname==\n\n[[File: Deng Xiaoping and Jimmy Carter at the arrival ceremony for the Vice Premier of China. - NARA - 183157-restored(cropped).jpg|thumb|[[Deng Xiaoping]] (\u9093\u5c0f\u5e73)]]\n\n* [[Deng Ai]], general of Cao Wei during the Three Kingdoms period\n* [[Deng Chao]], contemporary Chinese actor\n* [[Deng Zhi]], general of Shu Han during the Three Kingdoms period\n* [[Kent Deng]], economic historian and writer\n* [[Deng Longguang]] ({{lang|zh|\u9127\u9f8d\u5149}}), Chinese general in World War II \n* [[Deng Ming-Dao]], Taoist author\n* [[Deng Shichang]], Qing Dynasty admiral\n* [[Deng Shiru]] ({{lang|zh|\u9127\u77f3\u5982}}), calligrapher and seal carver\n* [[Deng Xiaoping]], former leader of China\n** [[Deng Pufang]], son of Deng Xiaoping\n** [[Deng Nan]], daughter of Deng Xiaoping\n* [[Deng Yingchao]], wife of Zhou Enlai\n* [[Deng Liqun]], leading figure of the Communist Party of China in the 1980s\n* [[Deng Yanda]], 1895-1931, a left-wing general who tried to create a middle ground between the Chinese Communists and Chiang Kai-shek\n* [[Deng Yaping]], table tennis player\n* Deng Yujiao, a Chinese woman involved in the [[Deng Yujiao incident]]\n* [[Alan Kwong-wing Tang]] ({{lang|zh|\u9127\u5149\u69ae}}), actor and movie producer\n* [[Tang Wing Cheung]] ({{lang|zh|\u9127\u6c38\u7965}}), birth name of Cantonese opera and film actor [[Sun Ma Sze Tsang]] ({{lang|zh|\u65b0\u99ac\u5e2b\u66fe}})\n* [[Chris Tang]] (\u9127\u70b3\u5f37), commissioner of Hong Kong police \n* [[H. T. Teng]], Taiwanese ichthyologist\n* [[Teresa Teng]], Taiwanese singer\n* [[Si-an Deng]], a Chinese-Canadian badminton player\n* [[Wendi Deng]], (birth name ''D\u00e8ng W\u00e9ng\u00e9'' or ''D\u00e8ng W\u00e9n G\u00e9'' (\u9093\u6587\u9769)) Chinese-American businesswoman, former wife of Rupert Murdoch\n* [[History of the Ming Dynasty#An open market, silver, and Deng Maoqi's rebellion|Deng Maoqi]] ({{lang|zh|\u9127\u8302\u4e03}}), leader of a tenant rebellion in [[Fujian]] at the end of the 1440s\n* [[Lydia Dunn, Baroness Dunn]], a [[crossbench]] [[House of Lords|British Peer]]\n* Patrick Dunn, ({{lang|zh|\u9127\u6893\u5cf0}}), Hong Kong TV personality\n* [[Sheren Tang]] ({{lang|zh|\u9127\u8403\u96ef}}), Hong Kong TVB actress\n* [[Lee C. Teng]], Chinese/Taiwanese scientist\n* [[G.E.M. (singer)|G.E.M.]] ({{lang|zh|\u9127\u7d2b\u68cb}}), HK Cantopop Singer-Songwriter\n* [[Kanny Theng]], Singaporean actress\n* [[Stephy Tang]] (born 1983), Hong Kong Cantopop singer and actress\n* [[Teng Chia-chi]], Deputy Mayor of [[Taipei]]\n\n==Notable people with surname \u9093\uff0f\u9127 (pinyin \"D\u00e8ng\") who use \"Tang\" in English==\n\n[[File:2018.09.22 \u5927\u8fde\u5546\u6f14 \u9093\u7d2b\u68cb (1).jpg|thumb|[[G.E.M.]] (\u9127\u7d2b\u68cb)]]\n\n* Tang Tsz-kei, [[G.E.M. (singer)]] (born 1991), Hong Kong singer\n* [[Stephy Tang]] (born 1983), Hong Kong Cantopop singer and actress\n* [[Sheren Tang]] Shui-man (born 2 March 1966) is a Hong Kong actress\n* [[Chris Tang]] Ping-keung, PDSM (Chinese: \u9127\u70b3\u5f37, born 4 July 1965 with family roots in Dongguan, Guangdong) is the current Commissioner of Police of the Hong Kong Police Force since 19 November 2019\n* [[Alan Tang]] Kwong-Wing (20 September 1946 \u2013 29 March 2011) was a Hong Kong film actor, producer and director.\n* [[Patrick Tang]] is a Hong Kong singer, actor, and TV show host who has been involved in numerous drama and movie productions\n* [[Shermon Tang]] Sheung Man (Chinese: \u9127\u4e0a\u6587) is a Hong Kong television actress of Hakka ancestry\n* [[Natasha Tang]] (born Tang Wing Yung, Chinese: \u9127\u7a4e\u6b23; Jyutping: dang6 wing6 jan1; 23 August 1992) is a Hong Kong distance swimmer\n* [[Billy Tang]] Hin-Shing (Chinese: \u9127\u884d\u6210) is a Hong Kong film director\n* [[Robert Tang]] Kwok-ching, GBM, SBS, JP (Chinese: \u9127\u570b\u6968; born 7 January 1947)[1] is a retired Hong Kong judge\n\n==Sudanese name==\nDeng is also a common first or last name used among the tribes of [[South Sudan]], shared by the [[Dinka people|Dinkas]], [[Nuer people|Nuers]] and [[Shilluk people|Shilluks]]. It has various meanings; for instance, it means \"Rain\" in Dinka. The Dinkas also believe that the most powerful god, ruler of all gods, is Deng{{Citation needed|date=February 2014}}.\n\n===Surname===\n* [[Ajou Deng]] (born 1978), South Sudan-born British basketball player; older son of Aldo (below)\n* [[Aldo Deng]], South Sudanese politician\n* [[Ataui Deng]], Sudanese-American model\n* [[Dominic Dim Deng]], South Sudanese military commander \n* [[Luol Deng]] (born 1985), South Sudan-born British basketball player; younger son of Aldo\n* [[Francis Deng]], South Sudanese politician \n* [[Peter Deng]], South Sudanese footballer\n* [[Thomas Deng]], Australian footballer\n* [[Valentino Achak Deng]], South Sudanese refugee and activists\n\n===Given name===\n* [[Deng Adel]] (born 1996), South Sudan-born Australian basketball player\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* http://www.oocities.org/thienwp/storyofdeng.htm\n\n{{100 Most Common Family Names in Mainland China}}\n{{surname}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Deng (Surname)}}\n[[Category:Chinese-language surnames]]\n[[Category:Individual Chinese surnames]]\n", "text_old": "\n\n{{distinguish|text=the surnames [[Teng (surname)|Teng]] ''(\u6ed5)'' or [[T\u00e1ng (surname)|T\u00e1ng]] ''(\u5510)''}}\n{{Infobox surname\n| name            = \u9127/\u9093\n| image           = \n| image_size      = \n| caption         = \n| romanization    = Teng ( [[Wade-Giles]] <br> [[Cantonese]]: Dahng ([[Yale romanization of Cantonese|Yale]]), Dang6 ([[Jyutping]]) <br>[[Southern Min|Minnan]]/[[Taiwanese Minnan|Taiwanese]]: T\u0113ng'' ( [[Pe\u030dh-\u014de-j\u012b]]) <br> [[Vietnamese language|Vietnamese]]: \u0110\u1eb7ng  <br>  [[Korean language|Korean]]: Deung \n| pronunciation   = D\u00e8ng\n| gender          = \n| feminine        = \n| masculine       = \n| language        = \n| languageorigin  = \n| origin          = [[Nanyang, Henan|Nanyang]], Henan [[Chinese clan#Tang hao|ancestral hall]] ({{lang|zh|\u5357\u967d\u5802}})\n| derivation      = \n| meaning         = \n| variant         = \n| cognate         = \n| anglicisation   = \n| derivative      = \n| seealso         = \n| family          = \n}}\n'''Deng''' is an [[East Asia]]n [[surname]] of Chinese origin. It is a transcription of [[wikt:\u9093|\u9093]] ([[simplified Chinese character]]) or [[wikt:\u9127|\u9127]] ([[Traditional Chinese character|traditional]]). It is transliterated as ''D\u00e8ng'' in [[pinyin]] and Teng, or Then, in [[Wade-Giles]]. In [[Cantonese]], it is ''Dahng'' in [[Yale romanization of Cantonese|Yale]] and ''Dang6'' in [[Jyutping]].  In [[Southern Min|Minnan]] or [[Taiwanese Minnan|Taiwanese]], it is ''T\u0113ng'' in [[Pe\u030dh-\u014de-j\u012b]]. The surname originating from the same Chinese character in [[Vietnamese language|Vietnamese]] is ''\u0110\u1eb7ng'' and it is one of the top ten surnames in [[Vietnam]]. The name is transliterated as ''Deung'' in [[Korean language|Korean]] but is very rare in [[Korea]]. Deng is one of the surnames of the [[Nanyang, Henan|Nanyang]], Henan [[Chinese clan#Tang hao|ancestral hall]] ({{lang|zh|\u5357\u967d\u5802}}).\n\nIn 2019 Deng was 21st most common surname in Mainland China.<ref>http://www.bjnews.com.cn/news/2020/01/20/676822.html</ref> \n\nIn addition to spelling \"Deng\" used in [[mainland China]], other common Chinese spelling variations include:\n* '''Tang''' - Romanization based on Cantonese spelling common in [[Hong Kong]] and [[Macao]]\n* '''Teng''' - Romanization based on Wade-Giles transliteration of [[Standard Mandarin|Mandarin Chinese]] common spelling in [[Taiwan]]\n\n==Notable persons with the surname==\n\n[[File: Deng Xiaoping and Jimmy Carter at the arrival ceremony for the Vice Premier of China. - NARA - 183157-restored(cropped).jpg|thumb|[[Deng Xiaoping]] (\u9093\u5c0f\u5e73)]]\n\n* [[Deng Ai]], general of Cao Wei during the Three Kingdoms period\n* [[Deng Chao]], contemporary Chinese actor\n* [[Deng Zhi]], general of Shu Han during the Three Kingdoms period\n* [[Kent Deng]], economic historian and writer\n* [[Deng Longguang]] ({{lang|zh|\u9127\u9f8d\u5149}}), Chinese general in World War II \n* [[Deng Ming-Dao]], Taoist author\n* [[Deng Shichang]], Qing Dynasty admiral\n* [[Deng Shiru]] ({{lang|zh|\u9127\u77f3\u5982}}), calligrapher and seal carver\n* [[Deng Xiaoping]], former leader of China\n** [[Deng Pufang]], son of Deng Xiaoping\n** [[Deng Nan]], daughter of Deng Xiaoping\n* [[Deng Yingchao]], wife of Zhou Enlai\n* [[Deng Liqun]], leading figure of the Communist Party of China in the 1980s\n* [[Deng Yanda]], 1895-1931, a left-wing general who tried to create a middle ground between the Chinese Communists and Chiang Kai-shek\n* [[Deng Yaping]], table tennis player\n* Deng Yujiao, a Chinese woman involved in the [[Deng Yujiao incident]]\n* [[Alan Kwong-wing Tang]] ({{lang|zh|\u9127\u5149\u69ae}}), actor and movie producer\n* [[Tang Wing Cheung]] ({{lang|zh|\u9127\u6c38\u7965}}), birth name of Cantonese opera and film actor [[Sun Ma Sze Tsang]] ({{lang|zh|\u65b0\u99ac\u5e2b\u66fe}})\n* [[Chris Tang]] (\u9127\u70b3\u5f37), commissioner of Hong Kong police \n* [[H. T. Teng]], Taiwanese ichthyologist\n* [[Teresa Teng]], Taiwanese singer\n* [[Si-an Deng]], a Chinese-Canadian badminton player\n* [[Wendi Deng]], (birth name ''D\u00e8ng W\u00e9ng\u00e9'' or ''D\u00e8ng W\u00e9n G\u00e9'' (\u9093\u6587\u9769)) Chinese-American businesswoman, former wife of Rupert Murdoch\n* [[History of the Ming Dynasty#An open market, silver, and Deng Maoqi's rebellion|Deng Maoqi]] ({{lang|zh|\u9127\u8302\u4e03}}), leader of a tenant rebellion in [[Fujian]] at the end of the 1440s\n* [[Lydia Dunn, Baroness Dunn]], a [[crossbench]] [[House of Lords|British Peer]]\n* Patrick Dunn, ({{lang|zh|\u9127\u6893\u5cf0}}), Hong Kong TV personality\n* [[Sheren Tang]] ({{lang|zh|\u9127\u8403\u96ef}}), Hong Kong TVB actress\n* [[Lee C. Teng]], Chinese/Taiwanese scientist\n* [[G.E.M. (singer)|G.E.M.]] ({{lang|zh|\u9127\u7d2b\u68cb}}), HK Cantopop Singer-Songwriter\n* [[Kanny Theng]], Singaporean actress\n* [[Stephy Tang]] (born 1983), Hong Kong Cantopop singer and actress\n* [[Teng Chia-chi]], Deputy Mayor of [[Taipei]]\n\n==Notable people with surname \u9093\uff0f\u9127 (pinyin \"D\u00e8ng\") who use \"Tang\" in English==\n\n[[File:2018.09.22 \u5927\u8fde\u5546\u6f14 \u9093\u7d2b\u68cb (1).jpg|thumb|[[G.E.M.]] (\u9127\u7d2b\u68cb)]]\n\n* Tang Tsz-kei, [[G.E.M. (singer)]] (born 1991), Hong Kong singer\n* [[Stephy Tang]] (born 1983), Hong Kong Cantopop singer and actress\n* [[Sheren Tang]] Shui-man (born 2 March 1966) is a Hong Kong actress\n* [[Chris Tang]] Ping-keung, PDSM (Chinese: \u9127\u70b3\u5f37, born 4 July 1965 with family roots in Dongguan, Guangdong) is the current Commissioner of Police of the Hong Kong Police Force since 19 November 2019\n* [[Alan Tang]] Kwong-Wing (20 September 1946 \u2013 29 March 2011) was a Hong Kong film actor, producer and director.\n* [[Patrick Tang]] is a Hong Kong singer, actor, and TV show host who has been involved in numerous drama and movie productions\n* [[Shermon Tang]] Sheung Man (Chinese: \u9127\u4e0a\u6587) is a Hong Kong television actress of Hakka ancestry\n* [[Natasha Tang]] (born Tang Wing Yung, Chinese: \u9127\u7a4e\u6b23; Jyutping: dang6 wing6 jan1; 23 August 1992) is a Hong Kong distance swimmer\n* [[Billy Tang]] Hin-Shing (Chinese: \u9127\u884d\u6210) is a Hong Kong film director\n* [[Robert Tang]] Kwok-ching, GBM, SBS, JP (Chinese: \u9127\u570b\u6968; born 7 January 1947)[1] is a retired Hong Kong judge\n\n==Sudanese name==\nDeng is also a common first or last name used among the tribes of [[South Sudan]], shared by the [[Dinka people|Dinkas]], [[Nuer people|Nuers]] and [[Shilluk people|Shilluks]]. It has various meanings; for instance, it means \"Rain\" in Dinka. The Dinkas also believe that the most powerful god, ruler of all gods, is Deng{{Citation needed|date=February 2014}}.\n\n===Surname===\n* [[Ajou Deng]] (born 1978), South Sudan-born British basketball player; older son of Aldo (below)\n* [[Aldo Deng]], South Sudanese politician\n* [[Ataui Deng]], Sudanese-American model\n* [[Dominic Dim Deng]], South Sudanese military commander \n* [[Luol Deng]] (born 1985), South Sudan-born British basketball player; younger son of Aldo\n* [[Francis Deng]], South Sudanese politician \n* [[Peter Deng]], South Sudanese footballer\n* [[Thomas Deng]], Australian footballer\n* [[Valentino Achak Deng]], South Sudanese refugee and activists\n\n===Given name===\n* [[Deng Adel]] (born 1996), South Sudan-born Australian basketball player\n\n==External links==\nhttp://www.oocities.org/thienwp/storyofdeng.htm\n\n{{100 Most Common Family Names in Mainland China}}\n{{surname}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Deng (Surname)}}\n[[Category:Chinese-language surnames]]\n[[Category:Individual Chinese surnames]]\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "Reflist", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deng_(surname)"}
{"title_page": "SEAL Team (TV series)", "text_new": "{{short description|2017 American military action drama television series}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = SEAL Team\n| image                = Seal Team TV Logo.png\n| image_alt            = \n| caption              = \n| genre                = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Action fiction|Action]]\n* [[Military drama]]\n}}\n| creator              = Benjamin Cavell\n| starring             = {{Plainlist|\n* [[David Boreanaz]]\n* [[Max Thieriot]]\n* [[Jessica Par\u00e9]]\n* [[Neil Brown Jr.]]\n* [[A. J. Buckley]]\n* [[Toni Trucks]]\n* Judd Lormand\n}}\n| theme_music_composer = \n| opentheme            = \n| endtheme             = \n| composer             = {{Plainlist|\n* [[W. G. Snuffy Walden]]\n* A. Patrick Rose\n}}\n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| num_seasons          = 3\n| num_episodes         = 61\n| list_episodes        = List of SEAL Team episodes \n| executive_producer   = {{Plainlist|\n* [[John Glenn (screenwriter)|John Glenn]] \n* Benjamin Cavell\n* [[Ed Redlich]]\n* Sarah Timberman\n* Carl Beverly\n* [[Christopher Chulack]]\n* David Boreanaz (2019\u2013)\n* Mark Owen\n}}\n| producer             = {{Plainlist|\n* Todd Lewis\n* Kate DiMento\n* Chris Leanza\n* David Boreanaz (2017\u20132019)\n}}\n| editor               = {{Plainlist|\n* Adam Wolfe\n* Mark Semos\n}}\n| cinematography       = {{Plainlist|\n* Gonzalo Amat\n* [[J. Michael Muro]]\n}}\n| camera               = [[Single-camera setup|Single-camera]]\n| runtime              = 43 minutes\n| company              = {{Plainlist|\n* Chulack Productions\n* East 25 C\n* Timberman/Beverly Productions\n* John Glenn Entertainment\n* [[CBS Television Studios]]\n}}\n| distributor          = [[CBS Television Distribution]]\n| network              = [[CBS]]\n| picture_format       = [[High-definition television|HDTV]] [[1080i]]\n| audio_format         = \n| first_aired          = {{Start date|2017|9|27}}\n| last_aired           = {{End date|present}}\n| website              = http://www.cbs.com/shows/seal-team/\n| production_website   = \n}}\n\n'''''SEAL Team''''' is an American [[military drama|military action drama]] television series created by Benjamin Cavell.<ref>{{cite web |last=Ausiello |first=Michael |url=http://tvline.com/2017/05/12/cbs-new-series-fall-2017-seal-team-swat/|title=CBS Orders Boreanaz' SEAL Team, Moore's S.W.A.T., Cumming's Instinct, Piven's Wisdom, Plus 2 Comedies|website=[[TVLine]] |date=May 12, 2017}}</ref> The series is produced by [[CBS Television Studios]], and began airing on [[CBS]] on September 27, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|url=http://deadline.com/2017/06/cbs-fall-2017-premiere-dates-young-sheldon-seal-team-9jkl-1202105923/|title=CBS Sets Fall 2017 Premiere Dates For 'Young Sheldon', '9 JKL' & Returning Series|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=June 1, 2017|accessdate=June 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe series follows an elite unit of [[United States Navy SEALs]] portrayed by [[David Boreanaz]], [[Max Thieriot]], [[Jessica Par\u00e9]], [[Neil Brown Jr.]], [[A. J. Buckley]], and [[Toni Trucks]]. On May 9, 2019, CBS renewed the series for a third season,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2019/05/09/cbs-renews-madam-secretary-bull-four-more-dramas/1155905001/|title=CBS renews 'Madam Secretary,' 'MacGyver,' 'Bull,' 'SEAL Team,' 'SWAT' and 'Hawaii Five-0' |last=Levin|first=Gary|work=[[USA TODAY]] |date=May 9, 2019|accessdate=May 9, 2019}}</ref> which premiered on October 2, 2019.<ref name=\"SeriesPremiereDate\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/06/cbs-fall-premiere-dates-bob-hearts-abishola-all-rise-evil-young-sheldon-ncis-blue-bloods-madam-secretary-1202632379/|title=CBS Sets Fall Premiere Dates: 'Bob \u2665 Abishola', 'All Rise', 'Evil', 'Young Sheldon', 'NCIS', 'Blue Bloods' & More|work=Deadline Hollywood|first1=Denise|last1=Petski|first2=Nellie|last2=Andreeva|date=June 13, 2019|accessdate=June 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Overview==\nThe series follows Bravo Team, a sub-unit of the [[United States Naval Special Warfare Development Group]],<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Borderlines |network=CBS |date=November 15, 2017 |series=SEAL Team |season=1 |number=7 |quote=We have one Dev Group operator in country and en route. |time=c. the 32 minute mark; the speaker is Mandy Ellis}}</ref><ref>{{Cite episode |title=The Exchange |network=CBS |date=November 22, 2017 |series=SEAL Team |season=1 |number=8 |quote=Whatever teams we go to, we're Tier One operators now |time=3 minute mark (of 59 minutes); the speaker is Trent}}</ref><ref>{{Cite episode |title=Getaway Day |network=CBS |date=January 31, 2018 |series=SEAL Team |season=1 |number=8}}.  The television news broadcast in the background of the wake specifically names the unit as Naval Special Warfare Development Group, commonly known as SEAL Team 6.</ref> the most elite unit of [[United States Navy SEALs|Navy SEALs]], as they plan and undertake dangerous missions worldwide with little notice, and the burden on them and their families.\n\n==Cast and characters==\n{{main|List of SEAL Team (TV series) characters}}\n\n* [[David Boreanaz]] as [[Master chief petty officer|Master Chief Special Warfare Operator]]{{ref|Ranks|A}} Jason Hayes a.k.a Bravo 1/1B, leader of a Navy SEAL team (Bravo Team) dealing with the recent loss of one of their own.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |last=Andreeva|first=Nellie |date=March 22, 2017 |title=David Boreanaz to Topline CBS' Navy SEAL Drama Pilot |url=http://deadline.com/2017/03/david-boreanaz-star-cbs-navy-seal-drama-pilot-recasting-jim-caviezel-1202048676/ |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]| accessdate=March 22, 2017}}</ref> (The character was originally to be played by [[Jim Caviezel]], but he bowed out of the project due to creative differences and was replaced by Boreanaz.<ref>[https://www.nola.com/entertainment_life/movies_tv/article_929baf10-0a71-5386-842a-cfc714379567.html Jim Caviezel bows out of NOLA-shot CBS pilot: report]</ref><ref>[https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/david-boreanaz-jim-caviezel-cbs-navy-seal-drama-pilot-1202014129/ David Boreanaz to Star in CBS Navy SEAL Drama Pilot]</ref>)\n* [[Max Thieriot]] as [[Petty officer, first class|Special Warfare Operator First Class]] (promoted from SO2 in Season 3) Clay Spenser a.k.a Bravo 6/6B, a second-generation Navy SEAL in training for [[Tier One (military)|Tier One]] status who is questioned as to his readiness for combat.<ref name=\"auto\"/>  He becomes a member of Bravo Team at the end of \"The Exchange\", and briefly served as the team's second-in-command following Senior Chief Ray Perry's assignment to Green Team.  \n* [[Jessica Par\u00e9]] as Amanda Ellis,<ref name=\"auto\"/> Bravo Team's [[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]] liaison. Due to her actions of giving up the location of a CIA asset in \"My Life For Yours,\" Mandy is demoted from her rank of officer and is now serving as an interrogator for the CIA.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tvline.com/2019/05/22/seal-team-recap-season-2-finale-episode-22-mandy-demoted/|title=SEAL Team Season 2 Finale Recap: Who Got Booted from Future Missions?|last=Mitovich|first=Matt Webb|last2=Mitovich|first2=Matt Webb|date=2019-05-23|website=TVLine|language=en|access-date=2019-06-01}}</ref> \n* [[Neil Brown Jr.]] as [[Warrant officer (United States)|Warrant officer]] Raymond \"Ray\" Perry a.k.a Bravo 2/2B, Jason's most trusted friend and the longest tenured member of the team.<ref name=\"auto\"/>  \n* [[A. J. Buckley]] as [[Petty officer, first class|Special Warfare Operator First Class]] Sonny Quinn a.k.a Bravo 3/3B, a loyal but sometimes volatile SEAL who is at his best in firefights and prefers them over a leadership position.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n* [[Toni Trucks]] as [[Ensign (rank)#United States|Ensign]] Lisa Davis, formerly [[Logistics specialist|Logistics Specialist]] [[Petty officer, first class|First Class]].<ref name=\"auto\"/>  and, since season 3, a DEVGRU Intelligence Officer assigned primarily to Bravo Team.\n* Judd Lormand as [[Lieutenant commander (United States)|Lieutenant Commander]] Eric Blackburn, Bravo Team's commanding officer (recurring season 1; main season 2\u2013present<ref name=\"lormand-s2\" />).\n\n{{Refbegin}}\n{{note label|Ranks|A|| Enlisted SEALs have Special Warfare Operator specific ratings. See [[United States Navy SEALs#Special warfare ratings|US Navy SEAL ratings]].}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n== Episodes ==\n{{Main|List of SEAL Team episodes}}\n{{:List of SEAL Team episodes}}\n\n== Production ==\n=== Development ===\nFollowing the success of History Channel's [[Six (TV series)|Six]], on January 27, 2017, it was announced that CBS had given the pilot order for another Navy SEAL project.<ref>{{cite web|last=Goldberg|first=Lesley|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/navy-seals-drama-lands-cbs-pilot-order-969328|title=Navy SEALs Drama Lands CBS Pilot Order|website=The Hollywood Reporter|date=January 27, 2017|accessdate=September 28, 2017}}</ref> The episode was written and authored by Benjamin Cavell who was expected to be an executive producer, alongside Ed Redlich, Sarah Timberman, Carl Beverly, [[Christopher Chulack]]. Production companies involved with the pilot include Chulack Productions, East 25 C, Timberman/Beverly Productions and [[CBS Television Studios]]. On May 12, 2017, CBS officially ordered the pilot to series.<ref>{{cite web|last=Holloway|first=Daniel|url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/cbs-series-orders-1202425010/|title=CBS Series Orders: '9JKL,' 'Me, Myself & I,' 'Instinct,' 'Wisdom of the Crowd,' 'Seal Team,' 'S.W.A.T.'|website=Variety|date=May 12, 2017|accessdate=September 28, 2017}}</ref> A few days later, it was announced that the series, now titled ''SEAL Team'', would premiere by September 27, 2017 and air on Wednesdays at 9:00 P.M.\n\nThe series received a full-season order on October 12, 2017, bringing the first season to a total of 22 episodes.<ref>{{cite web|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|url=http://deadline.com/2017/10/seal-team-gets-full-season-order-1202187465/|title='SEAL Team' Gets Full-Season Order From CBS|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=October 12, 2017}}</ref> On March 27, 2018, CBS renewed the series for a second season<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvline.com/2018/03/27/seal-team-renewed-cbs-season-2-swat/|title=SEAL Team, S.W.A.T. Renewed at CBS|last=Ausiello|first=Michael|publisher=[[TVLine]]|date=March 27, 2018|accessdate=March 27, 2018}}</ref> which premiered on October 3, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/07/cbs-fall-premiere-dates-2018-big-bang-theory-survivor-1202423513/|title=CBS Fall 2018 Premiere Dates: 'Big Bang' & 'Young Sheldon' To Help Launch 'Magnum PI' & 'Murphy Brown' Revival|work=Deadline Hollywood|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|date=July 9, 2018|accessdate=July 14, 2018}}</ref> On May 22, 2018, it was reported that both Cavell and Redlich were exiting their roles as executive producer and showrunner, and [[John Glenn (screenwriter)|John Glenn]] replacing him as showrunner.<ref>{{cite web|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|url=https://deadline.com/2018/05/seal-team-john-glenn-new-showrunner-benjamin-cavell-ed-redlich-exit-cbs-series-1202395982/|title='SEAL Team': John Glenn Joins CBS Series As New Showrunner, Two EPs Depart|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=May 22, 2018|accessdate=July 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Casting ===\nOn March 14, 2017 it was announced that [[Jim Caviezel]] would topline CBS' then-untitled Navy SEAL drama pilot<ref>{{cite web |title=Jim Caviezel To Topline Navy SEAL Drama Pilot In Return To CBS |url=https://deadline.com/2017/03/jim-caviezel-star-cbs-navy-seal-drama-pilot-1202043184/ |website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=16 November 2018 |date=14 March 2017}}</ref> but on March 22, 2017, it was announced that [[David Boreanaz]] had been cast in the pilot's lead role of Jason, replacing Caviezel.<ref name=\"auto\" /> On March 8, 2017, it was reported that [[A.J. Buckley]] would play Sonny.<ref name=\"cast-sonny\">{{cite web |title=A.J. Buckley Joins CBS' Navy SEAL Drama Pilot; Kevin Daniels In Jenny Lumet Project|url=https://deadline.com/2017/03/a-j-buckley-series-regular-cbs-navy-seal-drama-pilot-kevin-daniels-jenny-lumet-project-1202039250/ |website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=16 November 2018 |date=8 March 2017}}</ref> On August 15, 2018 it was reported that Judd Lormand had been upgraded to series regular for season 2.<ref name=\"lormand-s2\">{{cite web |title='SEAL Team': Judd Lormand Upped To Series Regular For Season 2 |url=https://deadline.com/2018/08/seal-team-judd-lormand-promoted-series-regular-season-2-1202445907/ |website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=15 November 2018 |date=15 August 2018}}</ref> On August 8, 2018, it was announced that [[Michael McGrady]] and Ruffin Prentiss would recur as Captain Harrington and Summer Kairos in the series' second season.<ref name=\"s2rec\">{{cite web |title='SEAL Team': Michael McGrady & Ruffin Prentiss To Recur On CBS Drama |url=https://deadline.com/2018/08/seal-team-michael-mcgrady-ruffin-prentiss-recur-cbs-drama-1202442171/ |website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=15 November 2018 |date=8 August 2018}}</ref> On July 10, 2019, it was reported that Jamie McShane and Rudy Dobrev were cast in recurring roles for the third season.<ref name=\"S3Recur\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/07/seal-team-jamie-mcshane-rudy-dobrev-recur-season-3-cbs-series-1202649248/|title='SEAL Team': Jamie McShane & Rudy Dobrev To Recur On Season 3|website=Deadline Hollywood|first=Denise|last=Petski|date=July 22, 2019|accessdate=July 22, 2019}}</ref> On August 7, 2019, [[Emily Swallow]] was cast in a recurring capacity for the third season.<ref name=\"EmilyS\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/08/why-women-kill-casts-li-jun-li-emily-swallow-seal-team-1202663000/|title='Why Women Kill' Casts Li Jun Li; Emily Swallow Joins 'SEAL Team'|work=Deadline Hollywood|first=Denise|last=Petski|date=August 7, 2019|accessdate=August 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Critical response===\nThe [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reported an approval rating of 70% based on 23 reviews, with an average rating of 5.66/10. The site's critical consensus reads, \"''SEAL Team''{{'s}} solidly written first season offers compelling characters and hints at broader potential, even if it's somewhat undermined by an overall sense of predictability.\"<ref name=\"RT\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/seal_team/s01|title=SEAL Team: Season 1|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=January 5, 2019}}</ref> [[Metacritic]], which uses a weighted average, assigned a score of 57 out of 100 based on 16 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/seal-team|title=SEAL Team - Season 1 Reviews|website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=September 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Ratings===\n{{Television season ratings\n| hide_18_49_rating = y\n| link1             = #Season 1 (2017\u201318)\n| episodes1         = 22\n| timeslot1         = Wednesday 9:00&nbsp;pm \n| start1            = {{Start date|2017|9|27}}\n| startrating1      = 9.88<ref name=\"1.01\">{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/daily-ratings/wednesday-final-ratings-sept-27-2017/|title='Survivor' premiere adjusts up: Wednesday final ratings|work=[[TV by the Numbers]]|last=Porter|first=Rick|date=September 28, 2017|accessdate=September 28, 2017}}</ref>\n| end1              = {{End date|2018|5|16}}\n| endrating1        = 6.14<ref name=\"1.22\">{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/daily-ratings/wednesday-final-ratings-may-16-2018/|title= 'Survivor' and 'The Blacklist' finale adjust up: Wednesday final ratings|work=TV by the Numbers|last=Porter|first=Rick|date=May 17, 2018|accessdate=May 17, 2018}}</ref>\n| season1           = 2017\u201318\n| rank1             = 28\n| viewers1          = 9.87<ref name=\"top50shows2018\">{{cite web|url=http://ew.com/tv/2018/05/31/top-