{"title_page": "Killsquad", "text_new": "{{COI|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Killsquad\n| image =\n| developer = [[Novarama]]\n| publisher = [[Novarama]]\n| engine = [[Unreal Engine|Unreal]]\n| released = July 16, 2019 (early access)\n| genre = [[Action RPG]]\n| modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]], [[Multiplayer video game|multiplayer]]\n| platforms = [[Steam (software)|Steam]]\n}}\n\n'''''Killsquad''''' is an action role playing game developed and published by [[Novarama]]. The game early access was released worldwide on [[Steam]], on July 16, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|title=Indie sci-fi ARPG Killsquad heads into early access in July|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/indie-sci-fi-arpg-killsquad-heads-into-early-access-in-july/|work=[[PC Gamer]]|accessdate=27 June 2019}}</ref> It is designed for 4 player online co-op play. The game is also playable single player. ''Killsquad'' is based on a science fiction universe where bounty hunter teams called Killsquads raid planets seeking for the little available resources left. It takes inspiration from 70s westerns, pulp fiction, as well as military science fiction such as ''[[Starship Troopers]]''.\n\n==Gameplay==\n''Killsquad'' focuses on short sessions, a live contract system shared by all connected players, and action-style control.\n<ref>{{cite web|title=Killsquad|url=https://store.steampowered.com/app/910490/Killsquad/|work=[[Steam (software)|Steam]]|accessdate= 7 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nUpon entering the game, players are presented with a contract browser. Bounty Hunter Contracts are being offered to all the community in real time, so players can either select one, or tag along with other players to fulfill missions together. Players can join forces with their friends on Steam, or tag along with complete unknowns. These contracts last approximately thirty minutes, and can be anything from hunting a large boss creature, escorting units, defending areas, etc.\n\nHeroes in ''Killsquad'' are class-based, and always start each contract at Level 1. Passive and active skills are specific to each hero, and can be available from the start, or unlocked as the contract progresses. By choosing skills, players can adapt their hero to the contract they need to undertake.\n\nHeroes also have a numeric value, the Vector. Vector is a metric of how good is the equipment currently assigned to that hero, be it weapons, or additional power-ups called Gears in the ''Killsquad'' universe. The Vector of a squad is a metric based on the Vectors of its team members. Fulfilling contracts and using the bounty to buy new weapons and gears is thus key, as Contracts require a certain vector to enter. If your squad has a Vector number below of the recommendation for the Contract, survival chances are lowered.\n\nKillsquad is a paid title, and so there is no microtransactions or loot boxes: once the contract is fulfilled, players get a reward in in-game currency, which they can spend on better weapons or equipment for their heroes.\n\nPlanets on ''Killsquad'' are procedurally generated in a way similar to [[Left4Dead]]: the layout of the map is built by an AI, which also controls the spawning of monsters, the quests offered to the team, the reward, to keep players engaged. Planets are considered as another enemy on ''Killsquad'', and so the AI can also spawn disasters to hamper the squad's progress, from meteor storms to minefields and police squads.\n\n===Multiplayer===\n''Killsquad'' is class oriented, and so combining different heroes with different skills is key to survival. Some heroes, like Kosmo, follow a classic tank pattern, with aggro, huge life pools and melee attacks, whereas others, like Zero, are healer-style characters, which allow the team to heal mid-mission.\n\n''Killsquad'' currently has 4 heroes to choose from, with more to be added later. The game is playable solo, but this is used mostly for training, as the main game mode is 4 player co-op. As of today, local co-op is not supported.\n\n==Plot==\n\n{{Empty section|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Reception==\nAt [[E3 2019]], ''Killsquad'' received an Unreal Award nomination for Most Engaging Game from [[Epic Games]].<ref>\n{{cite web|title=Unreal E3 Awards 2019 - Most Engaging|url=https://www.unrealengine.com/en-US/events/e32019/unreal-e3-awards-2019---most-engaging|work=[[Epic Games]]|accessdate=26 June 2019}}</ref> Upon previewing the title, Alana Hagues of the website ''RPGFan'' wrote: \"Killsquad was one of the biggest surprises at this year's E3 for me.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=E3 2019: Killsquad Preview|url=https://www.rpgfan.com/news/2019/9296.html|work=RPGFan|accessdate=26 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://store.steampowered.com/app/910490/Killsquad/}}\n\n[[Category:Multiplayer and single-player video games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Spain]]\n[[Category:Upcoming video games]]\n[[Category:Action role-playing video games]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Windows-only games]]\n[[Category:Video games using procedural generation]]\n", "text_old": "{{COI|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Killsquad\n| image =\n| developer = [[Novarama]]\n| publisher = [[Novarama]]\n| engine = [[Unreal Engine|Unreal]]\n| released = July 16, 2019 (early access)\n| genre = [[Action RPG]]\n| modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]], [[Multiplayer video game|multiplayer]]\n| platforms = [[Steam (software)|Steam]]\n}}\n\n'''''Killsquad''''' is an action role playing game developed and published by [[Novarama]]. The game early access was released worldwide on [[Steam]], on July 16th, 2019<ref>{{cite web|title=Indie sci-fi ARPG Killsquad heads into early access in July|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/indie-sci-fi-arpg-killsquad-heads-into-early-access-in-july/|work=[[PC Gamer]]|accessdate=27 June 2019}}</ref>. It is designed for 4 player online co-op play. The game is also playable single player. ''Killsquad'' is based on a science fiction universe where bounty hunter teams called Killsquads raid planets seeking for the little available resources left. It takes inspiration from 70s westerns, pulp fiction, as well as military science fiction such as ''[[Starship Troopers]]''.\n\n==Gameplay==\n''Killsquad'' focuses on short sessions, a live contract system shared by all connected players, and action-style control.\n<ref>{{cite web|title=Killsquad|url=https://store.steampowered.com/app/910490/Killsquad/|work=[[Steam (software)|Steam]]|accessdate= 7 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nUpon entering the game, players are presented with a contract browser. Bounty Hunter Contracts are being offered to all the community in real time, so players can either select one, or tag along with other players to fulfill missions together. Players can join forces with their friends on Steam, or tag along with complete unknowns. These contracts last approximately thirty minutes, and can be anything from hunting a large boss creature, escorting units, defending areas, etc.\n\nHeroes in ''Killsquad'' are class-based, and always start each contract at Level 1. Passive and active skills are specific to each hero, and can be available from the start, or unlocked as the contract progresses. By choosing skills, players can adapt their hero to the contract they need to undertake.\n\nHeroes also have a numeric value, the Vector. Vector is a metric of how good is the equipment currently assigned to that hero, be it weapons, or additional power-ups called Gears in the ''Killsquad'' universe. The Vector of a squad is a metric based on the Vectors of its team members. Fulfilling contracts and using the bounty to buy new weapons and gears is thus key, as Contracts require a certain vector to enter. If your squad has a Vector number below of the recommendation for the Contract, survival chances are lowered.\n\nKillsquad is a paid title, and so there is no microtransactions or loot boxes: once the contract is fulfilled, players get a reward in in-game currency, which they can spend on better weapons or equipment for their heroes.\n\nPlanets on ''Killsquad'' are procedurally generated in a way similar to [[Left4Dead]]: the layout of the map is built by an AI, which also controls the spawning of monsters, the quests offered to the team, the reward, to keep players engaged. Planets are considered as another enemy on ''Killsquad'', and so the AI can also spawn disasters to hamper the squad's progress, from meteor storms to minefields and police squads.\n\n===Multiplayer===\n''Killsquad'' is class oriented, and so combining different heroes with different skills is key to survival. Some heroes, like Kosmo, follow a classic tank pattern, with aggro, huge life pools and melee attacks, whereas others, like Zero, are healer-style characters, which allow the team to heal mid-mission.\n\n''Killsquad'' currently has 4 heroes to choose from, with more to be added later. The game is playable solo, but this is used mostly for training, as the main game mode is 4 player co-op. As of today, local co-op is not supported.\n\n==Plot==\n\n==Reception==\nAt [[E3 2019]], ''Killsquad'' received an Unreal Award nomination for Most Engaging Game from [[Epic Games]].<ref>\n{{cite web|title=Unreal E3 Awards 2019 - Most Engaging|url=https://www.unrealengine.com/en-US/events/e32019/unreal-e3-awards-2019---most-engaging|work=[[Epic Games]]|accessdate=26 June 2019}}</ref>. Upon previewing the title, Alana Hagues of the website ''RPGFan'' wrote: \"Killsquad was one of the biggest surprises at this year's E3 for me.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=E3 2019: Killsquad Preview|url=https://www.rpgfan.com/news/2019/9296.html|work=RPGFan|accessdate=26 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://store.steampowered.com/app/910490/Killsquad/}}\n\n[[Category:Multiplayer and single-player video games]]\n\n[[Category:Video games developed in Spain]]\n\n[[Category:Upcoming video games]]\n[[Category:Action role-playing video games]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Windows-only games]]\n[[Category:Video games using procedural generation]]\n", "name_user": "Nealbo", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up, added Empty section (1) tag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Killsquad"}
{"title_page": "Wellfield Botanic Gardens", "text_new": "{{short description|botanic gardens in Elkhart, IN}}\n{{Infobox park\n| name           = Wellfield Botanic Gardens\n| image          = \n| image_size     = \n| image_alt      = \n| image_caption  = \n| map            = <!-- or | map_image = --> \n| map_width      = \n| type           = \n| location       = [[Elkhart, Indiana|Elkhart, IN]]\n| nearest_city   = \n| coordinates    = {{coord|41.6964|-85.9800|format=dms|type:landmark_region:US-IN|display=inline,title}}\n| area           = \n| established    = 2005\n| operator       = \n| visitation_num = \n| status         = \n| designation    = \n| open           = Open year round, hours vary seasonally\n| parking        = Vehicle and bike parking available\n| administrator  = Wellfield Botanic Gardens Board of Directors\n| website        = https://wellfieldgardens.org\n}}\n\n'''Wellfield Botanic Gardens''', located in the heart of [[Elkhart, IN]], is a 36-acre natural enclave touted as a \"living museum\" and a working source of [[hydropower]] and drinking water. It is a [[501(c)(3) organization|501(c)3]] not-for-profit organization funded by private donations, earned revenue, memberships and grants.<ref name=history>{{cite web \n|url=https://wellfieldgardens.org/about-us/mission-and-history/ \n|title=Mission, Brief History, and Form 990 Financial Reporting \n|website= Wellfield Botanic Gardens\n|access-date=2019-03-09\n}}</ref>\n\n== Main Street Well Field History==\n\nA source of drinking water since at least 1885,<ref name=SBT>{{cite news \n|author=Stowe, Gene\n|title=Botanic gardens to flower on well field \n|publisher=[[South Bend Tribune]] Business Weekly \n|date=2007-02-26\n|volume=18\n|issue=9 \n}}</ref> the Main Street Well Field site was constructed in the early 1900s and serves as the primary water supply for Elkhart residents.\n\nGroundwater contamination resulting from industrial manufacturing runoff was identified at the site in 1981. Over the following decade, [[Superfund]] measures were put in place to correct these issues to the satisfaction of the [[United States Environmental Protection Agency|EPA]] and state authorities. There are currently 15 active wells that continue to be monitored.<ref>{{cite web \n|url=https://cumulis.epa.gov/supercpad/cursites/csitinfo.cfm?id=0501813\n|title=MAIN STREET WELL FIELD ELKHART, IN\n|website= [[United States Environmental Protection Agency]]\n|access-date=2019-03-09\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web \n|url=https://nepis.epa.gov/Exe/ZyNET.exe/91001M88.txt?ZyActionD=ZyDocument&Client=EPA&Index=1991%20Thru%201994&Docs=&Query=&Time=&EndTime=&SearchMethod=1&TocRestrict=n&Toc=&TocEntry=&QField=&QFieldYear=&QFieldMonth=&QFieldDay=&UseQField=&IntQFieldOp=0&ExtQFieldOp=0&XmlQuery=&File=D%3A%5CZYFILES%5CINDEX%20DATA%5C91THRU94%5CTXT%5C00000021%5C91001M88.txt&User=ANONYMOUS&Password=anonymous&SortMethod=h%7C-&MaximumDocuments=1&FuzzyDegree=0&ImageQuality=r75g8/r75g8/x150y150g16/i425&Display=hpfr&DefSeekPage=x&SearchBack=ZyActionL&Back=ZyActionS&BackDesc=Results%20page&MaximumPages=1&ZyEntry=1&slide\n|title=Superfund Record of Decision: Main Street Well Field, IN\n|author= United States Environmental Protection Agency\n|website= [[United States Environmental Protection Agency]]\n|access-date=2019-03-09\n|date= March 1991\n}}</ref>\n\n==The Wellfield Botanic Gardens==\n\nIn 2002, the Rotary Club of Elkhart conceived of the gardens as a community service project to celebrate the 100th anniversary of [[Rotary International]]. Modeled after the [[Frederik Meijer Gardens & Sculpture Park]] in Grand Rapids, Michigan, the goal was to create a community asset that served locals and tourists alike, preserving the natural habitat and contributing positively to the local economy.<ref name=SBT />\n\nThe project was officially handed over to the Wellfield Botanic Gardens Board of Directors in 2005 and construction began in 2006. Budgeted at approximately $11 million, construction was planned to take place in 7 phases over 10 years.<ref name=earthwork>{{cite web \n|url=https://indianaeconomicdigest.com/main.asp?SectionID=31&SubSectionID=62&ArticleID=31539\n|title=Earth-work starts on planned multi-million-dollar Elkhart County tourist attraction\n|author= Bridget Levitz\n|website= Indiana Economic Digest\n|access-date=2019-03-09\n|date=2007-01-18\n}}</ref>\n\nThe well field land remains the property of the City of Elkhart, and Wellfield Botanic Gardens signed a 99-year lease in 2005 to operate the not-for-profit botanic garden.<ref name=earthwork /><ref>{{cite web \n|url=https://wellfieldgardens.org/about-us/faq/\n|title=F.A.Q.s and Garden Etiquette \n|website=  Wellfield Botanic Gardens\n|access-date=2019-03-09\n}}</ref>\n\n==Garden Collections==\n\nWellfield Botanic Gardens features over 20 individual gardens including an English-style garden, a waterfall garden, and an \"Adventure Path\" for children.<ref name=gardens>{{cite web \n|url=https://wellfieldgardens.org/about/thegardens/\n|title=Garden Descriptions\n|website=Wellfield Botanic Gardens\n|access-date=2019-03-09\n}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Conversation Garden Walkway'' trail includes memorial pavers that can be purchased in memory of a loved one or to commemorate a special event.<ref>{{cite web \n|url=https://wellfieldgardens.org/get-involved/commemoratives/\n|title=Commemorative Pavers\n|website=Wellfield Botanic Gardens\n|access-date=2019-03-09\n}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Quilt Garden'' is updated yearly with flowerbeds and greenery designed to represent a quilt square. It is one of 17 quilt gardens in the northern Indiana Amish Country Heritage Trail.<ref>{{cite web \n|url=http://www.amishcountry.org/things-to-do/quilt-gardens/\n|title=Quilt Gardens Along the Heritage Trail\n|website=Heritage Trail Adventures\n|access-date=2019-03-09\n}}</ref>\n\nThe Japanese-style ''Island Garden'', slated to open in fall 2019, is being constructed under the guidance of Japanese garden expert [[Sadafumi Uchiyama]] and features boulders weighing up to {{convert|16000|lb|kg}}.<ref>{{cite web \n|url=https://www.elkharttruth.com/features/famed-japanese-garden-designer-working-at-wellfield-botanic/article_261ad08a-59e2-5daf-a3f9-fc54494737a2.html \n|title=Famed Japanese garden designer working at Wellfield Botanic \n|website= [[The Elkhart Truth]]\n|access-date=2019-03-09\n|date=2018-05-27\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web \n|url=https://wellfieldgardens.org/2019/01/19/do-you-know-your-hashi-from-a-hole-in-the-ground/\n|title=Do you know your hashi from a hole in the ground?\n|author= \n|website=Wellfield Botanic Gardens\n|access-date=2019-03-09\n|date=  \n}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Botanical gardens in the United States]]\n[[Category:Botanical gardens in Indiana]]\n[[Category:Elkhart, Indiana]]\n[[Category:Rotary International]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|botanic gardens in Elkhart, IN}}\n{{Infobox park\n| name           = Wellfield Botanic Gardens\n| image          = \n| image_size     = \n| image_alt      = \n| image_caption  = \n| map            = <!-- or | map_image = --> \n| map_width      = \n| type           = \n| location       = [[Elkhart, Indiana|Elkhart, IN]]\n| nearest_city   = \n| coordinates    = {{coord|41.6964|-85.9800|format=dms|type:landmark_region:US-IN|display=inline,title}}\n| area           = \n| established    = 2005\n| operator       = \n| visitation_num = \n| status         = \n| designation    = \n| open           = Open year round, hours vary seasonally\n| parking        = Vehicle and bike parking available\n| administrator  = Wellfield Botanic Gardens Board of Directors\n| website        = https://wellfieldgardens.org\n}}\n\n'''Wellfield Botanic Gardens''', located in the heart of [[Elkhart, IN]], is a 36-acre natural enclave touted as a \"living museum\" and a working source of [[hydropower]] and drinking water. It is a [[501(c)(3) organization|501(c)3]] not-for-profit organization funded by private donations, earned revenue, memberships and grants.<ref name=history>{{cite web \n|url=https://wellfieldgardens.org/about-us/mission-and-history/ \n|title=Mission, Brief History, and Form 990 Financial Reporting \n|website= Wellfield Botanic Gardens\n|access-date=2019-03-09\n}}</ref> \n\n== Main Street Well Field History==\n\nA source of drinking water since at least 1885,<ref name=SBT>{{cite news \n|author=Stowe, Gene\n|title=Botanic gardens to flower on well field \n|publisher=[[South Bend Tribune]] Business Weekly \n|date=2007-02-26\n|volume=18\n|issue=9 \n}}</ref> the Main Street Well Field site was constructed in the early 1900s and serves as the primary water supply for Elkhart residents. \n\nGroundwater contamination resulting from industrial manufacturing runoff was identified at the site in 1981. Over the following decade, [[Superfund]] measures were put in place to correct these issues to the satisfaction of the [[United States Environmental Protection Agency|EPA]] and state authorities. There are currently 15 active wells that continue to be monitored.<ref>{{cite web \n|url=https://cumulis.epa.gov/supercpad/cursites/csitinfo.cfm?id=0501813\n|title=MAIN STREET WELL FIELD ELKHART, IN\n|website= [[United States Environmental Protection Agency]]\n|access-date=2019-03-09\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web \n|url=https://nepis.epa.gov/Exe/ZyNET.exe/91001M88.txt?ZyActionD=ZyDocument&Client=EPA&Index=1991%20Thru%201994&Docs=&Query=&Time=&EndTime=&SearchMethod=1&TocRestrict=n&Toc=&TocEntry=&QField=&QFieldYear=&QFieldMonth=&QFieldDay=&UseQField=&IntQFieldOp=0&ExtQFieldOp=0&XmlQuery=&File=D%3A%5CZYFILES%5CINDEX%20DATA%5C91THRU94%5CTXT%5C00000021%5C91001M88.txt&User=ANONYMOUS&Password=anonymous&SortMethod=h%7C-&MaximumDocuments=1&FuzzyDegree=0&ImageQuality=r75g8/r75g8/x150y150g16/i425&Display=hpfr&DefSeekPage=x&SearchBack=ZyActionL&Back=ZyActionS&BackDesc=Results%20page&MaximumPages=1&ZyEntry=1&slide\n|title=Superfund Record of Decision: Main Street Well Field, IN\n|author= United States Environmental Protection Agency\n|website= [[United States Environmental Protection Agency]]\n|access-date=2019-03-09\n|date= March 1991\n}}</ref>  \n\n==The Wellfield Botanic Gardens==\n\nIn 2002, the Rotary Club of Elkhart conceived of the gardens as a community service project to celebrate the 100th anniversary of [[Rotary International]]. Modeled after the [[Frederik Meijer Gardens & Sculpture Park]] in Grand Rapids, Michigan, the goal was to create a community asset that served locals and tourists alike, preserving the natural habitat and contributing positively to the local economy.<ref name=SBT />\n\nThe project was officially handed over to the Wellfield Botanic Gardens Board of Directors in 2005 and construction began in 2006. Budgeted at approximately $11 million, construction was planned to take place in 7 phases over 10 years.<ref name=earthwork>{{cite web \n|url=https://indianaeconomicdigest.com/main.asp?SectionID=31&SubSectionID=62&ArticleID=31539\n|title=Earth-work starts on planned multi-million-dollar Elkhart County tourist attraction\n|author= Bridget Levitz\n|website= Indiana Economic Digest\n|access-date=2019-03-09\n|date=2007-01-18\n}}</ref>\n\nThe well field land remains the property of the City of Elkhart, and Wellfield Botanic Gardens signed a 99-year lease in 2005 to operate the not-for-profit botanic garden.<ref name=earthwork /><ref>{{cite web \n|url=https://wellfieldgardens.org/about-us/faq/\n|title=F.A.Q.s and Garden Etiquette \n|website=  Wellfield Botanic Gardens\n|access-date=2019-03-09\n}}</ref>\n\n==Garden Collections==\n\nWellfield Botanic Gardens features over 20 individual gardens including an English-style garden, a waterfall garden, and an \"Adventure Path\" for children.<ref name=gardens>{{cite web \n|url=https://wellfieldgardens.org/about/thegardens/\n|title=Garden Descriptions\n|website=Wellfield Botanic Gardens\n|access-date=2019-03-09\n}}</ref> \n\nThe ''Conversation Garden Walkway'' trail includes memorial pavers that can be purchased in memory of a loved one or to commemorate a special event.<ref>{{cite web \n|url=https://wellfieldgardens.org/get-involved/commemoratives/\n|title=Commemorative Pavers\n|website=Wellfield Botanic Gardens\n|access-date=2019-03-09\n}}</ref> \n\nThe ''Quilt Garden'' is updated yearly with flowerbeds and greenery designed to represent a quilt square. It is one of 17 quilt gardens in the northern Indiana Amish Country Heritage Trail.<ref>{{cite web \n|url=http://www.amishcountry.org/things-to-do/quilt-gardens/\n|title=Quilt Gardens Along the Heritage Trail\n|website=Heritage Trail Adventures\n|access-date=2019-03-09\n}}</ref> \n\nThe Japanese-style ''Island Garden'', slated to open in fall 2019, is being constructed under the guidance of Japanese garden expert [[Sadafumi Uchiyama]] and features boulders weighing up to {{convert|16000|lb|kg}}.<ref>{{cite web \n|url=https://www.elkharttruth.com/features/famed-japanese-garden-designer-working-at-wellfield-botanic/article_261ad08a-59e2-5daf-a3f9-fc54494737a2.html \n|title=Famed Japanese garden designer working at Wellfield Botanic \n|website= [[The Elkhart Truth]]\n|access-date=2019-03-09\n|date=2018-05-27\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web \n|url=https://wellfieldgardens.org/2019/01/19/do-you-know-your-hashi-from-a-hole-in-the-ground/\n|title=Do you know your hashi from a hole in the ground?\n|author= \n|website=Wellfield Botanic Gardens\n|access-date=2019-03-09\n|date=  \n}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Botanical gardens in the United States]]\n[[Category:Botanical gardens in Indiana]]\n[[Category:Elkhart, Indiana]]\n[[Category:Rotary International]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wellfield_Botanic_Gardens"}
